[{"id":"VR855936","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram consisting of, from left to right along a horizontal line, an object at point X, an object at point Y, and a concave mirror. Two tickmarks are indicated along the horizontal line, the first between point X and point Y, and the second between point Y and the mirror. The distance between the first and second tickmark is f. The distance between the second tickmark and the mirror is f. A note states that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR855936.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The figure shows a concave mirror with focal length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"f\"><math alttext=\"f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span> and the mirrorâ€™s principal axis. An object can be placed anywhere along the principal axis. Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span> is located a distance greater than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 f\"><math alttext=\"2 f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><mi>f</mi></math></span></span> from the mirror, and point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is located a distance less than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 f\"><math alttext=\"2 f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><mi>f</mi></math></span></span> but greater than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"f\"><math alttext=\"f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span> from the mirror. How do the images formed by the mirror compare between when the object is at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span> and when the object is at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span>? Specifically, how do the sizes (height magnitudes) and orientations (upright versus inverted) of the two images compare?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR855936_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The image size is greater when the object is at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>. The two images have the same orientation.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The image size is greater when the object is at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>. The two images have opposite orientations.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The image size is greater when the object is at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span>. The two images have the same orientation.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The image size is greater when the object is at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span>. The two images have opposite orientations.</p>"],"answer":2}]